Date: 21/10/1933
Source: Press, The
Author: GUTHRIE-SMITH
Vol / Page: 15
Edition:
Quote: <i> Futtah:</i> a station store, built on high posts to keep rats and mice out. Both the design and the name are borrowed from the Maoris. Some people used to call them watties. With the increasing use of iron and concrete they are becoming rare; the last built, I think, I put up at Braemar in 1910. (PAUL, p.90, where it is spelt wata; [1898 Morris Austral-English])
Notes: Acland Glossary

